 To improve their capabilities for independent thinking, teamwork, and critical analysis and develop their civil concern and spirit of service
□ 擴展國際視野、接受多元文化及跨領域學習
 To broaden their global vision and accept diverse cultures and interdisciplinary 
learning.
 

核心能力 Competence
■ 具備人文素養及社會關懷與服務的能力
 Ability to provide social concern and service with a spirit of humanity.
■ 具備語言學、語言教學理論、知識與應用能力
 Ability to apply professionally the knowledge and theory of linguistics and language teaching.
□ 英外語溝通及應用能力
 Ability to demonstrate foreign language proficiency in various applications.
□ 多面向深入閱讀、賞析外國文學、語言、文化與藝術的能力
 Ability to appreciate and analyze foreign literatures, languages and cultures from multi-dimensional perspectives.
■ 適應多元文化與職場領域的知能
 Abiltiy to accomodate diverse cultures and professional fields.
■ 培養獨立及批判性思考、提問及解決問題的能力
 Ability to think independently and critically and to raise questions and solve problems.
 

課程概述 Course Description
       社會語言學導讀：宏觀篇 This course introduces the interaction between language and social life in multilingual societies. It is designed for novices --any one interested in languages, literature, sociology, psychology, and behavior science. 
Since most societies in the world are composed of multilingual rather than monolingual speakers, we will first look at some important issues in multilingual societies. We focus on how languages develop as the official, national or vernacular language in a multilingual society; how language policy made to accommodate both the needs of cross-ethnic communication and maintenance of minority languages; how do political and economic factors affect speakers’ language choice, such as between Chinese and English?  
Each class meeting is composed of two parts: the teacher’s introducing general concepts in sociolinguistics with examples from various speech communities around the world, and students’ discussion and presentation of how these concepts are applied to the speech community they have observed or participated in. Non-native students should be reminded that while the text book provide rich examples of language use around the world, more examples situated in Taiwan, such as Austronesian languages and Chinese languages (including Hakka, Mandarin, and Hakka) will be cited for discussion. Students are also welcome to provide relevant examples from their native languages to enrich the learning.
    

課程學習目標 Course Objectives    
	    This course introduces the interaction between language and social life in multilingual societies. It is designed for novices --any one interested in languages, literature, sociology, psychology, and behavior science.
Since most societies in the world are composed of multilingual rather than monolingual speakers, we will first look at some important issues in multilingual societies. We focus on how languages develop as the official, national or vernacular language in a multilingual society; how language policy made to accommodate both the needs of cross-ethnic communication and maintenance of minority languages; how do political and economic factors affect speakers’ language choice, such as between Mandarin, Southern Min, Hakka, and English?     

